## Short Answer

ğŸ‘‰ **You should NOT package a full Next.js app as a reusable library**
ğŸ‘‰ **You SHOULD package reusable parts (UI, hooks, utils) separately**

---

## Why Full Next.js App â‰  Package

Next.js is **an application framework**, not a component library.

A Next.js app contains:

* Routing (`app/`, `pages/`)
* API routes (`app/api`)
* Server Components
* Middleware
* Build + runtime config
* Deployment logic

ğŸ“¦ **Packages are meant to be reusable logic**, not full apps.

So this is âŒ **NOT recommended**:

```text
@company/nextjs-app
```

---

## What You *CAN* Package from Next.js (Best Practice)

### âœ… 1. UI Component Package (MOST COMMON)

Create reusable components used across apps.

ğŸ“¦ `@company/ui`

```text
packages/
 â””â”€â”€ ui/
     â”œâ”€â”€ Button.tsx
     â”œâ”€â”€ DataGrid.tsx
     â”œâ”€â”€ Card.tsx
     â”œâ”€â”€ index.ts
```

Used inside Next.js:

```tsx
import { Button } from "@company/ui";
```

âœ” Works perfectly with Next.js
âœ” Tree-shakable
âœ” Reusable across teams

---

### âœ… 2. Hooks Package

Reusable hooks like auth, feature flags, data fetching.

ğŸ“¦ `@company/hooks`

```ts
export function useUser() {}
export function usePermissions() {}
```

---

### âœ… 3. Utils / Business Logic Package

Pricing logic, validation, formatters.

ğŸ“¦ `@company/utils`

```ts
